Revisiting the Index Construction of Proximity Graph-Based Approximate Nearest Neighbor Search

Shuo YangÂ§ Xidian University yangsh@stu.xidian.edu.cn ,Â  Jiadong XieÂ§ The Chinese University of Hong Kong jdxie@se.cuhk.edu.hk ,Â  Yingfan Liuâˆ— Xidian University liuyingfan@xidian.edu.cn ,Â  Jeffrey Xu Yu The Chinese University of Hong Kong yu@se.cuhk.edu.hk ,Â  Xiyue Gao Xidian University xygao@xidian.edu.cn ,Â  Qianru Wang Xidian University wangqianru@xidian.edu.cn ,Â  Yanguo Peng Xidian University ygpeng@xidian.edu.cn Â andÂ  Jiangtao Cui Xidian University cuijt@xidian.edu.cn
Abstract.

Proximity graphs (PG) have gained increasing popularity as the state-of-the-art (SOTA) solutions to kğ‘˜kitalic_k-approximate nearest neighbor (kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN) search on high-dimensional data, which serves as a fundamental function in various fields, e.g. information retrieval and retrieval-augmented generationÂ (RAG). Although PG-based approaches have the best kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN search performance, their index construction cost is superlinear to the number of points, since they have to identify close neighbors for each point to establish the edges. Such superlinear cost substantially limits their scalability in the era of big data. Hence, the goal of this paper is to accelerate the construction of PG-based methods without compromising their kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN search performance.

To achieve this goal, two mainstream categories of PG are revisited: relative neighborhood graph (RNG) and navigable small world graph (NSWG). By revisiting their construction process, we find the issues of construction efficiency. To address these issues, we propose a new construction framework with a novel pruning strategy for edge selection, which accelerates RNG construction while keeping its kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN search performance. Then, we integrate this framework into NSWG construction to enhance both the construction efficiency and kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN search performance. Moreover, extensive experiments are conducted to validate our construction framework for both RNG and NSWG. The results demonstrate that it significantly reduces the PG construction cost, achieving up to 5.6x speedup while not compromising the kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN search performance.

1. Introduction

Recent breakthroughs in deep learning models, specifically embedding models, have revolutionized the representation of various types of data, such as images and text chunks. These models transform the data into vectors, which encapsulate key information in a high-dimensional space for semantic analysis. As a result, kğ‘˜kitalic_k-approximate nearest neighbor (kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN) search on high-dimensional vectors has emerged as a fundamental problem across multiple domains, including information retrievalÂ (Grbovic and Cheng, 2018; Huang etÂ al., [n.â€‰d.]), recommendation systemÂ (Okura etÂ al., 2017) and large language modelsÂ (Barthel etÂ al., 2019; Lewis etÂ al., 2020; Guu etÂ al., 2020; Asai etÂ al., 2023; Liu etÂ al., 2024b). In particular, due to the popularity of retrieval-augmented generationÂ (RAG) (Lewis etÂ al., 2020; Asai etÂ al., 2023), kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN search on high-dimensional vectors causes more and more attention as a key RAG component. kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN search has been extensively studied for several decades, hence there exists a wealth of methods in the literatureÂ (Li etÂ al., 2019; Wang etÂ al., 2021a, 2017; Malkov etÂ al., 2014; Chen etÂ al., 2009; Tao etÂ al., 2009; Gan etÂ al., 2012; Liu etÂ al., 2014). According to recent studiesÂ (AumÃ¼ller etÂ al., 2020; Li etÂ al., 2020, 2019; Wang etÂ al., 2021a), the proximity graph (PG) based methods (Chen etÂ al., 2009; Dong etÂ al., 2011; Malkov etÂ al., 2014; Malkov and Yashunin, 2018; Li etÂ al., 2019; Fu etÂ al., 2019, 2022; Peng etÂ al., 2023) have emerged as the promising solution and have demonstrated superior performance compared to other approaches, such as hashing-based methods (Lv etÂ al., 2007; Tao etÂ al., 2009; Gan etÂ al., 2012; Liu etÂ al., 2014; Sun etÂ al., 2015; Huang etÂ al., 2016), invert index-based methods (Jegou etÂ al., 2011; Babenko and Lempitsky, 2014) and tree-based methods (Bentley, 1975; Berchtold etÂ al., 1996; Katayama and Satoh, 1997; Muja and Lowe, 2014). A PG treats each vector uâˆˆDğ‘¢ğ·u\in Ditalic_u âˆˆ italic_D as a graph vertex and then connects edges between uğ‘¢uitalic_u and its close neighbors. Notably, all PGs share the same vertex set but have various edge sets due to their distinct edge-selection strategies. According to previous studiesÂ (Peng etÂ al., 2023; Wang etÂ al., 2021a; Li etÂ al., 2019; Pan etÂ al., 2024), PGs are divided into three categories by different neighbor-selection strategies: kğ‘˜kitalic_k nearest neighbor graph (KNNG), relative neighborhood graph (RNG), and navigable small world graph (NSWG).

Although PG-based approaches have superior search performance, they still suffer from a significantly higher cost in terms of index construction than other methods. This is primarily due to the necessity of identifying close neighbors for each point to establish the graph edges. In the traditional applications of kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN search, PG index is built offline and then responds to kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN queries. Thus its construction cost is treated as a second-class performance indicator. However, in the emerging scenario, i.e., the RAG model trainingÂ (Guu etÂ al., 2020; Izacard etÂ al., 2023; Asai etÂ al., 2023), the PG index will be frequently built in an online manner, due to the tuning on the embedding model that transforms the source data such as text chunks into vectors. As a result, it is urgent to build PG efficiently while maintaining search performance. To address this issue, several studies have been proposed to accelerate the index construction, such as DiskANNÂ (Subramanya etÂ al., 2019), RNN-DescentÂ (Ono and Matsui, 2023), LSH-APGÂ (Zhao etÂ al., 2023) and ParlayANNÂ (Manohar etÂ al., 2024). 2.2. Beam Search

3.3. PG Construction Issues

As discussed above, we can see that both RNG and NSWG construction share the same procedure for each node uâˆˆDğ‘¢ğ·u\in Ditalic_u âˆˆ italic_D, i.e., finding a set of kğ‘˜kitalic_k close neighbors of uğ‘¢uitalic_u, denoted size-kğ‘˜kitalic_k candidate neighbor set acquisition (kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA), and then derive the PG by the ğ—‹ğ–¾ğ–¿ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ–¾ğ—†ğ–¾ğ—‡ğ—ğ—‹ğ–¾ğ–¿ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ–¾ğ—†ğ–¾ğ—‡ğ—\mathsf{refinement}sansserif_refinement phase that takes the kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA results as input. Due to the importance of the kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA results, there are two performance aspects of obtaining kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA, i.e., efficiency and quality. We present such an effect through the following experimental study.

The Importance of kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA Quality: For the PG derived from kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA results by ğ—‹ğ–¾ğ–¿ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ–¾ğ—†ğ–¾ğ—‡ğ—ğ—‹ğ–¾ğ–¿ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ–¾ğ—†ğ–¾ğ—‡ğ—\mathsf{refinement}sansserif_refinement phase, there are two aspects of its search performance, i.e., efficiency by queries per second (QPS) and accuracy by Râ¢eâ¢câ¢aâ¢lâ¢lâ¢@â¢10ğ‘…ğ‘’ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘™ğ‘™@10Recall@10italic_R italic_e italic_c italic_a italic_l italic_l @ 10 of returned kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN. The results clearly indicate that the kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA quality significantly impacts the search performance of the derived PG. Considering the strong relationship between the quality of kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA and search performance, we identify two issues in the construction of RNG and NSWG respectively.

RNG Construction Issue: RNG methods suffer from inefficiency in obtaining kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA results, caused by ğ—Œğ–¾ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–¼ğ—ğ—Œğ–¾ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–¼ğ—\mathsf{search}sansserif_search phase that takes the initial KNNG generated by ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ—‚ğ—ğ—‚ğ–ºğ—…ğ—‚ğ—“ğ–ºğ—ğ—‚ğ—ˆğ—‡ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ—‚ğ—ğ—‚ğ–ºğ—…ğ—‚ğ—“ğ–ºğ—ğ—‚ğ—ˆğ—‡\mathsf{initialization}sansserif_initialization phase as the graph index for accuracy improvement. As demonstrated in previous experimental studies (Li etÂ al., 2019; Wang etÂ al., 2021a), with similar (e.g. tens of ) average out-degrees, KNNG is more prone to local optima than RNG and NSWG due to directional edges and weak connectivity. To address this, RNG equips the initial KNNG with a pretty large (e.g. hundreds of) out-degree, which enhances the kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA quality but leads to an inefficiency issue. As depicted in FigureÂ 3(a), the search on KNNG to enhance the kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA quality constitutes a significant portion of the overall cost of building the representative RNG method (i.e., NSG), which even surpasses that taken for ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ—‚ğ—ğ—‚ğ–ºğ—…ğ—‚ğ—“ğ–ºğ—ğ—‚ğ—ˆğ—‡ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ—‚ğ—ğ—‚ğ–ºğ—…ğ—‚ğ—“ğ–ºğ—ğ—‚ğ—ˆğ—‡\mathsf{initialization}sansserif_initialization on the ğ–¦ğ—‚ğ—Œğ—ğŸ£ğ–¬ğ–¦ğ—‚ğ—Œğ—ğŸ£ğ–¬\mathsf{Gist1M}sansserif_Gist1M dataset. A similar phenomenon could be found in other RNG methods such as Ï„ğœ\tauitalic_Ï„-MNG.

NSWG Construction Issue: NSWG methods suffer from a poor kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA quality in construction, caused by its building strategy of incremental node-by-node insertions: utilizes the current graph index with only a part of nodes to conduct kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN search for kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA results. Hence, the expected value of kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA quality in NSWG is only 0.50.50.50.5 even if all the kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN queries are answered correctly. Since achieving exact correctness in kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN queries is not feasible, the average recall in practice is upper bounded by 0.50.50.50.5, as demonstrated in FigureÂ 2(b).

4. Refinement Before Search

5. A New PG Construction Framework

In this section, we provide comprehensive details of our new construction framework for RNG and NSWG. 5.2. Self-Iterative Construction of RNG

According to our refinement-before-search scheme, we could generate the final RNG index by applying another ğ—‹ğ–¾ğ–¿ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ–¾ğ—†ğ–¾ğ—‡ğ—ğ—‹ğ–¾ğ–¿ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ–¾ğ—†ğ–¾ğ—‡ğ—\mathsf{refinement}sansserif_refinement on the results of OptKCNA. However, such a simple construction strategy still faces the following challenges, in order to balance the kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA efficiency and quality.

Difficulty of Tuning Parameters in ğ–²ğ–¾ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–¼ğ—ğ–²ğ–¾ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–¼ğ—\mathsf{Search}sansserif_Search Phase: In the ğ—Œğ–¾ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–¼ğ—ğ—Œğ–¾ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–¼ğ—\mathsf{search}sansserif_search phase, Lğ¿Litalic_L is the key parameter to the efficiency-quality balance and thus should be carefully selected. However, the best choice of Lğ¿Litalic_L varies from datasets. Grid search is commonly employed for finding the best Lğ¿Litalic_LÂ (Wang etÂ al., 2021a; Li etÂ al., 2019), which builds a corresponding graph index for each potential Lğ¿Litalic_L value with a huge cost. Hence, this one-shot strategy of setting Lğ¿Litalic_L is considerably time-consuming.

To address this issue, we take the progressive strategy of tuning Lğ¿Litalic_L and propose a self-iterative framework with two key components, i.e., quality examination and iterative refinement. The former determines the termination condition of our framework, while the latter defines the behaviour in each iteration. Again, we use the NSG as the representative RNG to illustrate the details.

To address this issue, we estimate the kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA quality via sampling. We then delve into determining the value of nssubscriptğ‘›ğ‘ n_{s}italic_n start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_s end_POSTSUBSCRIPT to ensure that the estimation obtained through random sampling possesses a theoretical guarantee. As mentioned in the previous section regarding the NSWG construction issue, the poor kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA quality primarily arises due to the incremental node-by-node insertion strategy and the ğ—Œğ–¾ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–¼ğ—ğ—Œğ–¾ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–¼ğ—\mathsf{search}sansserif_search conducted on the current incomplete graph index that includes only a portion of nodes. In this part, we still use HNSW as the representative NSWG index, and propose a global construction of HNSW, which achieves kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA results on whole data points in each layer instead of only a part.

Our global construction of HNSW is built on top of a layer-by-layer insertion strategy in a top-down manner. To be specific, we first determine the layers for each node before the actual layer insertion and thus we obtain the whole set of nodes in each layer. Afterward, we employ our RNG construction framework in SectionÂ 5.2 to build a graph index for each layer. In this way, each layer of HNSW is built on top of kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA results w.r.t the whole set of nodes in each layer instead of only a subset. Hence, the kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA quality of each layer will significantly exceed 0.5 (i.e., the upper bound in the original HNSW). Note that each layer of HNSW is actually an RNG index, since it takes the RNG pruning strategy to prune the kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA results only without the connectivity enhancement via DFS. Subsequently, we insert the RNG index of the layer into HNSW according to the layer-by-layer insertion strategy.

The details of our HNSW construction are presented in AlgorithmÂ 7. Initially, we randomly determine the layer of each node, following the same approach as in the original HNSW (Lines 1-3). Then, we select one node at the top layer as the entry node eâ¢pğ‘’ğ‘epitalic_e italic_p (Line 4). The index construction proceeds from the top layer to the bottom layer (Line 5). For nodes in each layer (Line 6), we directly connect them if the number of nodes does not exceed the out-degree limit Mğ‘€Mitalic_M (Lines 7-8). Alternatively, we apply our optimized NSG construction to obtain the index (Lines 9-10).

5.5. Summary

The pipeline of our framework is summarized in FigureÂ 1(c). In the beginning, we obtain a KNNG through the ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ—‚ğ—ğ—‚ğ–ºğ—…ğ—‚ğ—“ğ–ºğ—ğ—‚ğ—ˆğ—‡ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ—‚ğ—ğ—‚ğ–ºğ—…ğ—‚ğ—“ğ–ºğ—ğ—‚ğ—ˆğ—‡\mathsf{initialization}sansserif_initialization phase and then enter an iterative loop to continuously enhance the kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA quality until it satisfies the quality examination or achieves the required number of iterations. During each iteration, we first obtain an intermediate graph index from the current kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA results via a new pruning strategy for neighbor selection in the ğ—‹ğ–¾ğ–¿ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ–¾ğ—†ğ–¾ğ—‡ğ—ğ—‹ğ–¾ğ–¿ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ–¾ğ—†ğ–¾ğ—‡ğ—\mathsf{refinement}sansserif_refinement phase. Subsequently, we perform a beam search for each node in the ğ—Œğ–¾ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–¼ğ—ğ—Œğ–¾ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–¼ğ—\mathsf{search}sansserif_search phase to enhance the kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA quality. The optimization techniques, i.e., ğ–ªğŸ¤ğ–¯ğ–ªğŸ¤ğ–¯\mathsf{K2P}sansserif_K2P and ğ–¯ğŸ¤ğ–ªğ–¯ğŸ¤ğ–ª\mathsf{P2K}sansserif_P2K, further accelerate the ğ—‹ğ–¾ğ–¿ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ–¾ğ—†ğ–¾ğ—‡ğ—ğ—‹ğ–¾ğ–¿ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ–¾ğ—†ğ–¾ğ—‡ğ—\mathsf{refinement}sansserif_refinement and ğ—Œğ–¾ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–¼ğ—ğ—Œğ–¾ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–¼ğ—\mathsf{search}sansserif_search phases respectively.

It is important to note that our framework is not only well-suited for NSG and HNSW, as detailed in this section, but also could be extended to the construction of other SOTA PGs, such as Ï„ğœ\tauitalic_Ï„-MNGÂ (Peng etÂ al., 2023) and NSWÂ (Malkov etÂ al., 2014) (as demonstrated in Exp.5 in SectionÂ 6). This is due to the fact that the construction pipelines of all SOTA PGs fall into the two categories we have discussed.

7. Related Works

There have been a bulk of works on processing kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN queries on high-dimensional data in the literature. To answer a kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN query, index structures are widely used to carefully select a small part of high-quality candidates and then verify them via distance computations, in order to return accurate results with little cost. According to recent experimental studies (AumÃ¼ller etÂ al., 2020; Li etÂ al., 2020, 2019; Wang etÂ al., 2021a), proximity graphs (Fu etÂ al., 2019; Malkov and Yashunin, 2018; Fu etÂ al., 2022) outperform other index structures such as hashing-based methods (Datar etÂ al., 2004; Lv etÂ al., 2007; Liu etÂ al., 2014; Sun etÂ al., 2015), inverted index-based methods (Jegou etÂ al., 2011; Babenko and Lempitsky, 2014) and tree-based methods (Bentley, 1975; Muja and Lowe, 2014) in search performance. Due to their excellent search performance, the SOTA PG methods such as NSG (Fu etÂ al., 2019) and HNSW (Malkov and Yashunin, 2018) have been taken as the solution by industrial vector databases such as MilvusÂ (Wang etÂ al., 2021b) and VBaseÂ (Zhang etÂ al., 2023).

Moreover, several works that combine the parallel power of GPU and the filtering capacity of PG methods have been proposedÂ (Zhao etÂ al., 2020; Groh etÂ al., 2022; Yu etÂ al., 2022; Ootomo etÂ al., 2023; Liu etÂ al., 2024a). SONG (Zhao etÂ al., 2020) modifies the search method of existing methods such as HNSW in order to achieve higher throughput. Other GPU-accelerated methods such as GGNN (Groh etÂ al., 2022), GANNS (Yu etÂ al., 2022) and CAGRA (Ootomo etÂ al., 2023) build their own graph index and have the corresponding search method. In addition, there exist I/O-efficient PG-based approaches, such as DiskANN (Subramanya etÂ al., 2019) and Starling (Wang etÂ al., 2024). Besides, some work expands kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN search to various scenarios, such as hybrid search (Zhang etÂ al., 2023; Gollapudi etÂ al., 2023; Zuo etÂ al., 2024), out-of-distribution queriesÂ (Jaiswal etÂ al., 2022), and search on billion-scale datasetsÂ (Chen etÂ al., 2021; JayaramÂ Subramanya etÂ al., 2019; Ni etÂ al., 2023).

8. Conclusion

In this paper, we study the efficient construction of the SOTA proximity graph-based approaches for kğ‘˜kitalic_k-ANN search and start by revisiting existing PG construction approaches. We analyze the importance of kğ‘˜kitalic_k-CNA quality on their construction efficiency and search performance, and figure out their issues on construction. To address these issues, we propose a novel construction framework for RNG with Î±ğ›¼\alphaitalic_Î±-pruning strategy and a self-iterative framework. We then combine the layer-by-layer insertion strategy with our RNG construction framework to address the construction issue of HNSW (i.e., the representative NSWG). Finally, we conduct extensive experiments on real-world datasets to showcase the superiority of our methods. The results show our approaches exhibit a construction speedup to 5.65.65.65.6x faster than the original methods of RNG and NSWG while delivering comparable or even superior search performance.
